git push won&#x27;t work, I am getting this error message:

{code}
#!python

remote: error: unable to create temporary file: No space left on device
remote: fatal: failed to write object
error: unpack failed: unpack-objects abnormal exit
{code}

I found other tickets with the same problem, but they all are marked resolved, so I&#x27;m creating this one.

Specific error is &#x27;mercurial.hook in _pythonhook\\
HookAbort: pretxncommit hook failed&#x27;

Unable to add wiki to HG repository, and there is no current workaround until this bug is resolved.

This appears to be breaking applications with invalid responses: https://github.com/nodegit/nodegit/issues/911

{code}
#!python

[Error: HTTP parser error: unexpected content-length header]
{code}

We realize this might break Bamboo Cloud functionality, but it&#x27;s more than likely an easy fix on our end. Let&#x27;s keep this ticket a placeholder so we can have people subscribe to any updates involving this

In markdown containing bash code, "cd" is highlighted such that it looks like a comment. In the example below, I would expect "cd" to appear the same as "mkdir".

{code}
#!bash
# This is a comment
mkdir ~/repo
cd ~/repo
{code}

FWIW the resulting HTML span element corresponding to "cd" has the class "nb" (I haven&#x27;t been able to work out which language feature this corresponds to, comments appear to have the class "c1").

Leave SourceTree running for a night, and try to pull the next day. It appears to take forever:

{code}
#!batch

git -c diff.mnemonicprefix=false -c core.quotepath=false fetch origin
{code}

Pulling works as expected after restarting SourceTree. I&#x27;m using Bitbucket as origin so bug 6495 might be related.

Doing the following:

{code}
#!python

git branch &#x27;#branch&#x27;
{code}

..will make a branch that is not linked correctly in the Bitbucket Commit UI once pushed up

The bug BCLOUD-11196 is still there. You can see it on my project overview here https://bitbucket.org/kr41/greenrocket

I&#x27;ve made an investigation and found out that it happens because of conflicting CSS rules. Styles {{.wiki-content .error}} apply on elements {{.wiki-content .code .error}}. So the fast fix could be:

{code}
#!css

/* Add this to wiki-content.css, line 166 */
.wiki-content .code .error {
 background: none;
 border: none;
 margin: 0;
 padding: 0;
}
{code}

